'''Filippo Cavolini''' (8 April 1756, [[Vico Equense]] – 15 March 1810, [[Naples]] ) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[Marine biology|marine biologist]].
The son of Nicola Cavolini, a Neapolitan lawyer, and Angela Auriemma, Filippo Cavolini left a legal career to devote himself to natural history. He became the Professor of Zoology at the [[University of Naples]] and Director of the [[Zoological Museum of Naples|Zoological Museum]]. His research style, similar to that of [[Lazzaro Spallanzani]], led to important results in the arena of marine biology and botany (''Memorie per servire alla storia de' polipi marini'' -1785- ''Memoria per servire alla generazione dei pesci e dei granchi'' - 1787). He died following an assault by a soldier while he was researching by boat in the [[Gulf of Naples]]: he fell into the sea and died a few days later from [[pneumonia]]. The opisthobranch family [[Cavoliniidae]] honours his name.
==References== *M. Alippi Cappelletti, «CAVOLINI, Filippo». In : ''Dizionario biografico degli italiani'', Vol. XXIII (Cavallucci-Cerretesi), Roma : Istituto della Enciclopedia Italiana, 1979 (on-line) *S.Delle Chiaie, ''Memorie postume sceverate dalle schede di Filippo Cavolini'' [1], Benevento,1853
